<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-297-984  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 297 984.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>High Technology Business  June 1989 v9 n6 p14(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The high-tech needs of the Postal Service. (automation of USPostal Service)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Layne, Abner.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Between 1989 and 1993 the US Postal Service (USPS) plans to spend$12.9 billion on a capital investment program to further automateoperations, including $4.6 billion for mail-processing equipment.andO;The primary benefit of automation is cost: it costs 3.3 cents toprocess a letter manually, compared to 0.3 cents automatically.andO;Bar coding is one of the key technologies in the USPS's automationefforts, which are advancing on two fronts: the near-term, whichis pursued by the Engineering andamp; Technical Support Department; andthe long term, which is pursued by the Technology ResourcesDepartment.andP;  The specific functions of each department aredescribed.andP;  One of the greatest technological challenges facingthe USPS is character recognition, especially of hand-addressedmail.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Postal ServiceEconomics of ComputingCostApplicationsResearch and DevelopmentCapital InvestmentGovernment AgencyNational GovernmentCharacter RecognitionRobotsBar CodesOptical Character Readers.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>